obliterated all of his work. Then he was taken ill and did not recover."\par
"Too bad," Frank murmured.\par
Chet, still hoping to keep the Hardys working at his project, asked how Cap's aunt expected him to find the camel when it was covered up.\par
"I haven't told you all the story," Cap replied. "Before he died, my uncle scratched out a rough map of the section, with the location of his original discovery indicated on it. He called the place 'Wildcat Swamp.' "\par
That was all Chet needed. "Wildcats!" he exclaimed, and concentrated his attention on the excavation job.\par
His shovel fairly flew as he tried to ignore any more of the conversation, but under his breath the others could hear him muttering:\par
"Train robbers-wildcats-swamps-ugh!"\par
"The reason my uncle called the place Wildcat Swamp," Cap Bailey went on, "was that not far from the site of his discovery he had found a sign reading: 'Here lie the bodies of twenty wildcat.' "\par
"That's strange," Joe remarked. "The killer must have been a mighty hunter."\par
Bailey nodded, and considered his two young friends. "I guess anyone going into the area would have to keep his eyes open. And, incidentally, I've already found out there is some danger to even starting for the spot."\par
"What do you mean?" the boys chorused.\par
