When the butcher's driver saw the gun, his jaw fell.\par
"What's the big idea?" he shouted.\par
"You may be carrying an escaped prisoner!"\par
The driver went white as the warden approached the rear doors of his truck and flung them open.\par
"If Turk was ever in here, he's gone now," Duckworth said disappointedly. "I'll radio the other men."\par
Frank and Joe got out and spoke to the truckman. "Do you mind if we have a look inside your truck?"\par
"Go ahead."\par
Climbing into the cool interior, the boys began examining it carefully for clues to the missing convict.\par
"Here's something," cried Frank almost immediately, as he picked up a small wooden box. "Why, it looks like some kind of homemade radio set."\par
It proved to be a miniature receiving set, so small that it fit snugly in the palm of Frank's hand. As he turned a knob, the gadget began to sputter.\par
"Repeating Turk," it suddenly announced. "Freight delayed. Hook 138576 at three Rock Spring."\par
As suddenly as it had begun, the voice broke off.\par
"That sounded like Flint's voice!" shouted the warden. "I'm sure that was Flint!"\par
"But what did all the gibberish mean?" queried Joe. "Was Flint in on Turk's escape?"\par
A Dangerous Chase 13\par
"Might have been," Duckworth retorted tersely. "Turk worked in the electrician's shop in the prison and took several courses in radio mechanics while he was there. He may have rigged up this communications system as part of a planned break."\par
"So when Flint and Willie the Penman got out they could tip him off on how to get away," Joe suggested.\par
"That's the way it might have worked," agreed the officer.\par
" 'Freight delayed. Hook 138576 at three Rock Spring,' " Frank repeated. "Sounds as if a railroad freight may be part of the plan. You said Turk was a locomotive engineer at one time, didn't you?"\par
"That's right!"\par
"I don't know what 'Hook 138576' could mean, but three Rock Spring might mean time and place. It's almost three o'clock now-and Rock Spring isn't far from here!"\par
"Let's get moving. Rock Spring in a big hurry!" Duckworth shouted at his police driver, and they scrambled aboard for the mile and a half drive to the railroad line.\par
"There's a water tower on the line at Rock Spring," Joe recalled. "But the road doesn't go in that far, Warden."\par
"We'll have to make the last half mile on foot."\par
Reaching the end of the bumpy country road, they all jumped out of the warden's car and headed\par
14 The Secret of Wildcat Swamp\par
for the rail line. Frank and Joe, still in good condition from track work during the spring, soon outdistanced the others. But before they reached the right-of-way they could hear the heavy thunder of a freight train.\par
"Maybe we're too late," Frank said, puffing. "Hey! Here comes a car numbered 138576! I'll bet that's what the message meant!"\par
Before Frank could answer, the car had rumbled past them. Suddenly the sliding door of the boxcar began to glide open. Then, as car 138576 moved still farther ahead of the boys, a large, well-padded hook was extended from the interior.\par
"Look, Frank!" Joe shouted. "That man!"\par
Out of the bushes alongside the right-of-way dashed a burly figure. Timing his sprint perfectly, he pulled up just as the hook reached him. With a desperate grab he caught it, and was immediately drawn inside the car. The freight thundered on.\par
"That must have been Turk!" Frank exclaimed.\par
By the time they reached the rails, the caboose had rolled by. The boys ran along the track behind the caboose for a short distance. There was no trainman in sight to hear their shouts or see their frantic signals.\par
Minutes later, Warden Duckworth and the driver caught up with them. Frank breathlessly explained the strange getaway of the fugitive they believed to be Turk.\par
A Dangerous Chase 15\par
"I'll phone from my car," the warden said, "and have the freight searched at the next station."\par
Contacting the prison, he asked the operator to relay the message to the railroad authorities. Then they drove back and waited in his office for word. When the report came, it was discouraging. The railroad police had opened car 138576 at the next stop, ten miles ahead, but had found it empty.\par
"Turk and his buddy inside must have seen you boys and were smart enough to sense that someone was on their trail. They must have left the train somewhere along the stretch between where Turk got aboard and the next town. But we'll catch up with Turk somewhere. Prisoners don't break out of here and stay out-very long!"\par
The Hardys remained in the warden's office for a while, hoping that there would be further news of the fugitive. When none was forthcoming they agreed that they should get home as quickly as possible and tell Mr. Hardy of the escape of Turk.\par
"This convinces me that Flint is up to his old tricks again," Mr. Hardy said. "But to what extent I can't tell. All I do know is that there has been a series of freight train robberies throughout the country, and it's up to me to figure out how to put a stop to them."\par
"Who engaged you to take this case, Dad?" Joe asked.\par
"The North American Railroad League. That's\par
16 The Secret of Wildcat Swamp\par
a group of railroad executives. They've been losing a lot of property in train robberies, and believing that the various thefts were the acts of a single gang of bandits, they think I can break up the racket."\par
Mr. Hardy then went on to explain that the robbers, so far as he had been able to find out, had used either of two methods in their plan of operation.\par
"Sometimes," he said, "they throw a road block at strategic points, where the engineer can't see it in time to stop his train. In this way they create wrecks and make their hauls during the confusion.\par
"At other times they manage to send false messages by radio, and induce the train crew to switch certain boxcars to specified lonely sidings. Then they just move in and loot them."\par
"Sounds like a pretty slick outfit," Joe remarked. "They seem to have their organization well lined up."\par
"Yes, they have. That's what makes them so tough to handle," his father affirmed.\par
"Dad," Joe asked, "do you suppose the phrase 'twenty wildcat' is some kind of password?"\par
Frank, who had been listening quietly, offered an additional idea. "It's possible that the railroad thieves have some kind of headquarters near where Cap's uncle was digging for the fossil. Maybe a cache where they hide their loot."\par
"That would certainly account for their not wanting any strangers in that immediate territory," Mr.\par
A Dangerous Chase 17\par
Hardy agreed. "They may have been trying to discourage Bailey by holding him up on that first trip. As a matter of fact, they probably planned to steal the map his uncle left."\par
The Hardys spent another half-hour considering various angles to the case, then the boys' father said he must get some papers ready for a flying trip to New York.\par
"I'm getting the eleven-o'clock plane, so I'll be there first thing in the morning for a conference with the League officials," he explained.\par
After a taxi had taken Fenton Hardy to the airport, the boys discussed their own trip, and the clothes and equipment they ought to take.\par
"I suppose we'll be on horseback a lot of the time," Frank remarked.\par
It was nearing midnight before the brothers had their gear packed. They were about to start for bed when the telephone's shrill ring disturbed the peace of the big, frame house.\par
Frank answered the call, as Joe stood near by. A woman's voice, edged with hysteria, said:\par
"This is Mrs. Bailey, Frank. I've already called the police, but I think you should know what has happened here."\par
"What, Mrs. Bailey?"\par
"Two masked men broke into our house and ransacked it. They attacked my husband and left him unconscious!"\par
